Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Co-operative Bank, BAT Kenya, Finbank

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-05-05T16:27:35Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-05/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-co-operative-bank-bat-kenya-move.html
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index declined for
a second day, falling 0.5 percent to 2,050.56 by the 1:30 p.m.
close in Port Louis, the largest drop since March 18.  Kenya’s All-Share Index rose for a fourth day, adding 0.5
percent to 76.39 by the 3 p.m. end of trading in Nairobi, the
highest close since March 4. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index added 0.6 percent to 25,219.69 by 2:30 p.m. close in
Lagos, according to a statement on the bourse’s website.
Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  fell 0.6 percent to 842.04
by the 4 p.m. end of trading in Windhoek, the lowest since March
18. The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index gained 0.1 percent
to 1,141.02 at the 3 p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  British American Tobacco Kenya Ltd. (BATK)  , climbed to
its highest level in almost a week, advancing 1 shilling, or 0.4
percent, to 262 shillings. East Africa’s biggest cigarette maker
plans to begin exports to  Southern Sudan  this year, Managing
Director Gary Fagan said yesterday.  Co-operative Bank of Kenya Ltd. (COOP)  , the East African
nation’s fourth-biggest lender by assets, gained 15 cents, or
0.9 percent, to 17.65 shillings, after the Nairobi-based
Business Daily newspaper reported the bank plans to create 1.3
billion new shares, taking the number of shares to 5 billion.  Finbank Plc (FIRSTINL)  , a Nigerian lender bailed out by
the  central bank  in 2009, advanced 1 kobo, or 1.4 percent, to 73
kobo, its highest since March 30, after Governor Lamido Sanusi
said it signed an agreement with potential investors. First City
Monument Bank Plc signed a memorandum of understanding to merge
with and recapitalize Finbank.  Oceanic Bank International Plc (OCEANIC)  , a Nigerian
lender bailed out two years ago, rose 8 kobo, or 4.5 percent, to
1.87 naira, gaining for a fourth day. The Central Bank of
 Nigeria  said it isn’t “desperate to sell” the bank following
the collapse of talks for First Bank of Nigeria to recapitalize
the lender.  Total Petroleum Ghana Ltd. (TOTAL)  , a fuel retailer in
the West African nation, rose to the highest on record after the
company declared a final dividend of 67.6 pesewas a share. The
stock climbed 44 pesewas, or 2.7 percent, to 16.79 cedis.  To contact the reporter on this story:
